            <h2><strong> Environment & Age Indicators </strong></h2>
            </br>
            <h4> <strong>Environmental Indicators </strong></h4>
            <p> Fossils can be useful for determining various clues of the past, including the ecologic conditions at a certain interval of time and the depositional environments .  They may also be used to determine the energy associated with the environment at the time, for instance, heavy shelled organisms are indicators of high energy conditions while softer-delicate shelled organisms are associated with environments of lower energy conditions like lagoons .
  	        Organisms of the present are also studied to understand the life style of organisms of the past . There are also studies aimed at establishing the relationship between organisms and the environment they need to live .  For instance, various animals prefer sandy or muddy bottoms; others need to live in the photic zone and others live firmly attached to the seafloor .  Filter feeders need currents to bring them food and others need special conditions for reproduction .  It’s important to note that fossils may be transported to areas where the environment does not represent the living conditions of the organism .  That is why in order to obtain accurate, meaningful information; geologists must try to collect an assemblage of fossils in a formation or an area. </p>
            </br>
            <h4> <strong>Index Fossils</strong></h4>
            <p>Fossils  in general can be used to determine relative geologic age, paleoenvironment and the paleogeography of a particular area .  However, there exists certain “Index fossils” which are fossils especially useful for determining ages .  In order for a fossil to be considered an index fossil, it must meet the following criteria:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><p> The organism must have lived throughout a relatively short period of geologic time due to rapid evolution and should be abundant.</p></li>
              <li><p> The organism should have a wide geographic distribution and must be facies independent. </p></li>
              <li><p> The organism must be relatively easy to identify. </p></li>
            </ul>
            
            <p> In order to determine the age of rock strata, the following technique should be employed:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><p> Identification of each fossil’s phylum level followed by the determination of the specific name.</p></li>
              <li><p> Once the genus or species is known, the geologic range of the fossils is plotted on a geologic time diagram.</p></li>
              <li><p> Three assumptions must be made .  First, all fossil have been collected from the same formation or horizon representing one period of deposition .  Second, all fossil organisms lived together and represent life during a single interval of geologic time .  Third, the geologic range of each fossil is known.</p></li>
            </ul>
